2026-04-16 12:39:50 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal return/ground reference network (sensor & relay return node)', 'control module PCB trace or connector between relay/sensor return node and true ground'] hypothesis_explanation='All measurements show a solid 12 V from the power supply into the control module, and a solid 0 V reference at the control output negative terminal and power‑supply negative conductor (continuity ~0.1 Ω). Yet the relay coil and sensor network both share a return node that sits at about 0.36 V above the module’s true ground. The relay coil positive is at ~11.99 V and its return is at ~0.36 V, so only ~11.6 V is actually across the coil, but more importantly that 0.36 V offset is abnormal for a simple low‑side return.\n\nThe fact that: (1) the module input supply rails are correct and stable, (2) the positive supply path inside the module shows essentially no drop, (3) the output negative terminal is at true 0 V, and (4) the only abnormal voltage is the elevated shared return node for the relay and light‑sensor circuit, strongly indicates a fault local to that internal ground/return reference network. This could be a cracked PCB trace, a bad solder joint, or a partially open connector between the sensor/relay return node and the true ground reference.\n\nBecause replacing the relay contacts and driver circuitry did not change the behavior, the root cause is most likely an open or high‑resistance connection in the internal return/ground path that ties the relay and sensor return node to the module’s true ground. Repairing/replacing that ground reference network (or the PCB trace/connector implementing it) should restore correct operation and eliminate the lamp’s periodic drop‑outs and current inability to turn on.'
