2026-04-16 12:40:20 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal wiring of relay contacts to output connector (positive side)', 'control module output connector / cabling from relay contact to load module (+)'] hypothesis_explanation='All diagnostics show the control module electronics and returns are healthy: \n- 12 V is present at the control‑module input and on the internal positive rail.\n- The relay coil sees nearly full supply (≈12 V to ≈0.36 V), so it is being driven correctly.\n- The light‑sensor network and indicator LED behave normally; their node voltages are as expected.\n- The negative/return conductor from the PSU through the control module to the output is solid (0 V at output −, good continuity).\n\nYet the voltage at the control‑module output to the load is only about 0.36 V instead of ≈12 V when the relay should be closed. This means the fault lies between the relay contact’s switched positive node and the external output terminal that feeds the load module.\n\nThe only remaining plausible cause is a discontinuity or mis‑wiring on the positive side of the switched path: either the relay’s movable contact is not actually connected to the output connector pin (e.g., wrong PCB trace, unsoldered joint, or connector pin not wired), or the short cable/connector from the control module output (+) to the load module is open/high‑resistance. Both would produce a near‑zero voltage at the measured output while all internal control circuitry appears normal.\n\nTherefore I hypothesize a fault in the internal wiring/PCB trace from the relay contacts to the output connector, or in the immediate output connector/cable on the positive side, preventing 12 V from reaching the load.'
