2026-04-16 12:40:45 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module switched‑cables indicator LED circuit (including its series resistor and any misconnection to the positive rail)'] hypothesis_explanation='The control module has solid 12 V at its input and on all internal positive‑supply nodes. The negative/return path from the power supply into the control module is also intact (near 0 V and low resistance). Yet the relay/sensor return node sits at ~0.36 V above ground, and the relay output to the load never rises above ~0.36 V while the lamp is off.\n\nThe switched‑cables indicator LED was suspected as a possible clamp on this node. Direct measurements show its anode at about 1.29 V and its cathode at 0 V, meaning the LED is forward‑biased from the relay/sensor return node (≈0.36 V) toward ground via some series resistance. This LED path is sinking current from the relay/sensor return, holding that node at a low, but non‑zero voltage (~0.36 V) instead of letting it rise or fall as the relay and control circuitry require.\n\nAll other hypothesized faults—relay contacts and driver, internal ground reference, and positive‑output wiring—have been ruled out by both measurements and explicit repair attempts. Cable polarity and inter‑module connections are verified correct. The only remaining consistent explanation is that the switched‑cables indicator LED circuit itself is faulty or miswired: for example, its anode tied to the relay/sensor return when it should reference the positive rail, or its series resistor/connection shorted so that it continuously loads and clamps the return node.\n\nA fault in this LED circuit would:\n1) Leave the main module supply and ground correct (matching observations),\n2) Load the relay/sensor return so that it never reaches proper levels to energize the relay or generate a clean 12 V output (explaining the persistent ~0.36 V at both relay return and output +),\n3) Be consistent with the measured 1.29 V across the LED and its anode near the abnormal 0.36 V node.\n\nTherefore the most probable root cause is a defect or misconnection in the control module’s switched‑cables indicator LED circuit, which is incorrectly clamping the relay/sensor return node and preventing normal relay operation.'
