2026-04-16 12:41:12 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module protection diode D_series (orientation / symbol polarity error)'] hypothesis_explanation='All supply and control‑module checks show a healthy 12 V source, correct polarity, intact relay drive circuitry, correct ground reference, and no abnormal clamping by the switched‑cables indicator LED. Yet whenever 12 V is applied directly to the load module, both lamps remain at ~0 V on both terminals, while the series protection diode’s anode sits at ~0.36 V and its cathode at 0 V. This indicates that essentially the entire applied voltage is being dropped somewhere ahead of the diode, and only a small forward drop (~0.36 V) appears on what is labelled the anode, with the downstream lamp node never rising above ground. That behaviour is inconsistent with a correctly oriented series diode feeding a normal lamp load from a solid 12 V source.\n\nThe repeated ~0.36 V level observed in multiple places (control‑module output, load‑module diode anode, etc.) matches the forward drop of a silicon diode biased in the reverse direction through leakage or through an internal body‑diode path, not a fully forward‑biased element driving a load. Since continuity of the lamps and wiring inside the load module is nominal, the remaining plausible internal fault is that the series protection diode itself is installed or wired with its polarity reversed relative to the labelled 12 V line, or its symbol/pin designation on the PCB is incorrect so that what is marked as the anode is actually the cathode. In that case, when 12 V is applied correctly, the diode is reverse‑biased and blocks current to the lamps; only a small leakage‑related or measurement‑artfact voltage (~0.36 V) appears, keeping the lamp node effectively at 0 V.\n\nTherefore the most likely single root cause is a polarity/orientation fault of the load‑module protection diode in series with the lamp circuit. Repair would involve correcting the orientation or PCB connection of this diode so that it conducts when 12 V is correctly applied and blocks only when polarity is truly reversed.'
