2026-04-16 12:42:05 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module internal positive output connection from battery/indicator node to external + terminal (connector, wiring, or PCB trace)'] hypothesis_explanation='All measurements show a healthy 12 V battery and that the internal PSU green LED, wired in parallel with the source, is lit and sees the correct forward voltage between the internal + and 0 V rails. However, whenever we reference the external + output terminal of the power‑supply module (whether feeding the control module, the load module directly, or under any configuration), the voltage collapses to about 0.36 V relative to ground. The external − terminal is solidly at 0 V and has good continuity to the rest of the system; the fault consistently affects only the + rail as presented at the PSU output connector.\n\nThe control and load modules have both been extensively tested and even when they are bypassed, connecting the PSU output directly to the load still yields only ~0.36 V on the load positive input and the lamps remain dark, though the PSU LED continues to indicate proper internal battery voltage. This behavior is consistent with an open or very high‑resistance connection between the internal positive node (where the battery and PSU indicator LED are connected) and the external positive output terminal. The residual ~0.36 V appearing at downstream points is likely due to leakage paths and measurement loading, not a working supply.\n\nTherefore, the most probable single point of failure is the internal positive output path of the power‑supply module—from the battery/indicator junction to the external + output connector (broken solder joint, fractured PCB trace, faulty connector pin, or similar). Repairing or replacing this internal positive output connection should restore a full 12 V to the rest of the system and allow the control and load modules to operate normally.'
