2026-04-16 12:42:19 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module battery (12 V source cell)'] hypothesis_explanation='All modules’ wiring, connectors, polarity, indicator LED circuits, relay, sensor network, and load-module diode and returns have been tested or temporarily bypassed and found electrically sound. Yet whenever the load module is connected to the power supply (either through the control module or directly), the positive rail collapses to about 0.36 V while the negative rail remains at 0 V. The same ~0.36 V level is seen at the control-module output, relay return, and load-module diode anode under supposed 12 V drive conditions. This behavior is characteristic of a severely depleted or high‑internal‑resistance battery whose open‑circuit voltage is near nominal but which sags to a few hundred millivolts under even a modest load. The power-supply status LED can still light at very low current, falsely suggesting normal operation, while there is insufficient voltage/current to drive the relay coil or lamps. Therefore the root cause is a faulty 12 V battery in the power supply module; replacing the battery should restore normal operation (steady lamp on when the control module commands it).'
