2026-04-16 12:42:59 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module output connector polarity / labeling (PSU Output Cable (+) and PSU Output Cable (−) swapped or shorted together)', 'shared ground / measurement reference connection used in prior tests'] hypothesis_explanation='All functional subcircuits (battery, control module relay/sensor path, load module diode and lamps) have now been independently verified as non‑faulty through repairs that had no effect and through direct tests. Yet two key anomalies remain:\n\n1) When the PSU is tested with the control module bypassed and only the load module attached, the PSU Output Cable (+) and PSU Output Cable (−) both measure ~11.99 V **relative to the external “ground” reference**, giving essentially 0 V differential between them. Nevertheless, the battery itself is at 12.0 V, and the PSU indicator LED anode sits correctly at ~1.29 V above the true PSU negative. Battery current is only ~12 mA and does not change with the load connected, indicating the load is effectively not across the battery at all.\n\n2) Earlier, when the PSU was feeding the control module, a correct ~11.99 V differential was measured **between the two control‑module input terminals**, and the control electronics behaved plausibly (relay coil seeing ~12 V across it, light‑sensor bias correct, etc.). This means that electrically the PSU can and does provide 12 V differential across its two output conductors into the control module.\n\nReconciling these facts implies that the fault is not inside the PSU, control, or load modules individually, but in how the PSU output conductors are identified / referenced externally:\n- The measurements showing both PSU Output Cable (+) and (−) at ~11.99 V were taken relative to an assumed “ground” node that is actually tied to the battery **positive** terminal (through the LED reference), not to the battery negative. In other words, the external labeling or wiring of the PSU output connector is inverted or shorted to the wrong reference.\n- When the control module is inserted, it is wired consistently to that mislabeled connector, so it still sees ~12 V between its input pins and therefore operates, but the subsequent attempt to drive the load module and the direct‑PSU‑to‑load tests are referenced to the wrong polarity, leaving the lamp at only ~0.36 V effective forward bias.\n\nThus, the root cause is a polarity / labeling error or mis‑wiring at the **power supply module output connector**, specifically involving the PSU Output Cable (+) and PSU Output Cable (−) conductors (and the external ground reference used in previous measurements). Correcting this connector polarity/labeling so that the conductors truly correspond to battery positive and battery negative, and are not both tied near +12 V with respect to the measurement ground, should restore proper 12 V differential to the control and load modules and allow the lamp to operate continuously without the observed anomalies.'
